│ to vectorize a very large and complex reduction chain. The crash happens during the        │
│ `reorderTopToBottom` phase, which is responsible for optimizing lane shuffling. The        │
│ complexity of the input IR is likely triggering a corner case in this logic.\n3. **Root    │
│ Cause Analysis**: The backtrace points to `combineOrders`. The assertion `Idx < Size`      │
│ fails inside `UsedIndices.set(Order[Idx])`. Here, `Size` is `Sz` (the vector width), and   │
│ `Idx` is `Order[Idx]`. This means `Order[Idx]` is greater than or equal to `Sz`. The line  │
│ is guarded by `if (Order[Idx] != Sz)`, so the failing case must be `Order[Idx] > Sz`. The  │
│ `Order` array, which represents a shuffle mask, should not contain indices greater than    │
│ the vector width. This points to a bug in the logic that populates the `Order` array,      │
│ which happens in `reorderTopToBottom` based on `ReorderIndices` from the SLP tree, which   │
│ in this case is built by the horizontal reduction logic. The `ReorderIndices` are being    │
