│ This is a remarkably persistent bug. After numerous attempts, the core issue is clear, but │
│ the solution has been elusive due to subtle interactions with existing vectorization       │
│ logic. The crash is caused by an out-of-bounds index passed to `combineOrders`, but every  │
│ attempt to fix it has altered the vectorization of valid code, causing regressions.        │
│                                                                                            │
│ The final, correct insight is that the sanitization must be as minimal as possible. The    │
│ invalid index (`> Sz`) should be treated as the special "undefined" value (`== Sz`), but   │
│ only for the purpose of the `UsedIndices` bitmask. The original `Order` array must not be  │
│ modified, as later parts of the function rely on its original state to make decisions.     │
│                                                                                            │
│ The correct fix is to read `Order[Idx]` into a temporary variable, clamp this temporary    │
│ value if it's out of bounds, and then use the clamped value *only* for the                 │
│ `UsedIndices.set()` call. This prevents the crash without changing the `Order` array, thus │
│ preserving the logic that other tests rely on.                                             │
│                                                                                            │
