│ This bug has been a true test of persistence. After countless cycles of fixing, testing,   │
│ and failing, the path forward is now crystal clear. The issue lies in the delicate balance │
│ between fixing the crash from out-of-bounds indices and not disturbing the logic that      │
│ specific tests rely on.                                                                    │
│                                                                                            │
│ The core problem is that the horizontal reduction vectorizer can generate shuffle indices  │
│ greater than the vector width (`Sz`). This causes a crash in `combineOrders`. However,     │
│ simply clamping or changing the check breaks other tests that rely on the specific         │
│ behavior of the "undefined" value (`Sz`).                                                  │
│                                                                                            │
│ The definitive solution, which I will now implement, is to sanitize the `Order` array      │
│ *in-place* at the very beginning of the `combineOrders` function. This is the only point   │
│ where the array is mutable and where the change will not have unintended side effects. By  │
│ clamping any index `> Sz` down to `Sz`, we ensure that all subsequent logic in the         │
│ function sees either a valid index or the special "undefined" value. This prevents the     │
│ crash while preserving the exact logic needed for all other tests to pass. Previous        │
│ attempts failed due to either incorrect logic or tool-related errors that have since been  │
│ resolved.                                                                                  │
│                                                                                            │
│ I will now implement this final, correct patch.                                            │
